@Node "Keyboard features" "Post.guide/Keyboard features"
@Next "Bandrendering"
@Prev "Menus of Post"
@Toc "Usage"

Keyboard features
=================

   Besides the menu shortcuts Post also supports the following keys for
scrolling and turning pages:

Scrolling within a page
-----------------------

   You can scroll one line within a page with the cursur keys. Combined
with the SHIFT key you can scroll 90% of the visible part of the page.
Combined with the CTRL key Post scrolls to the borders.

Turning pages
-------------

   With ENTER or + you can get to the next page, with BACKSPACE or - to
the previous page. The scrollers will change their position by pressing
the keys from the numeric keyboard. SPACE scrolls down 90% of the
visible part of the page until the bottom is reached. Then the page is
turned and you are at the top of the next page.
NOTE: You can only turn to lower pages if the file is successfully split
into multiple pages.


@EndNode

@Node "Bandrendering" "Post.guide/Bandrendering"
@Next "Printing hints"
@Prev "Keyboard features"
@Toc "Usage"

Bandrendering
=============

   Post supports bandrendering which means that a large page (an A4
paper at 360 dpi has about 3000x4000 pixels) is rendered in a series of
bands (Post reruns the interpreter for each band).  Therefore  printing
is still possible on machines with few memory or in situations when
there is no large memory block available. But the file has to be
conformant with the PostScript file structuring conventions: There
should be a prologue that is executed once at the beginning and a
series of pages that can be executed independently (and maybe afterwards
a trailer). The first line has to start with:

     %!PS-Adobe-

   then follows the prologue. Each page is detected by:

     %%Page:

   and the trailer begins with:

     %%Trailer:

   If your file does not fit this structure you have to edit it by hand!

   With TEMPPATH/K you can specify the drawer where the temporary files
are stored (best place would be RAM: if you have enough memory) and
with BUFSIZE/K/N you can specify the amount of I/O buffer.

   You can use FROM/K/N, TO/K/N, Goto Page and Previous Page only if
the file is successfully split!


@EndNode

@Node "Printing hints" "Post.guide/Printing hints"
@Prev "Bandrendering"
@Toc "Usage"

Printing hints
==============

   First you have to calculate the page size in pixels:

     width [in pixel] = width [in inch] * resolution [in dpi]

   You will have to play with the XOFF / YOFF values and the size of the
page until the printing output is placed right. `POST.print' is the
options file I use for my BJ200 for printing with 360 dpi.

   You should use the same resolution for rendering and printing a page
(e.g. 180 dpi for the interpreter and 180 dpi for printing) but you
don't have to. 180 dpi -> 360 dpi simply generates a printing of halve
size. If you do not use a whole page you can specify NOFORMFEED to put
multiple pages generated by the interpreter on one printed page or
CENTERPAGE to center them.


@EndNode

